        "content": "Web search results for query: \"NVIDIA datacenter GPU VRAM memory capacity H100 A100 H200 B200 L40S A10 V100 GB\"\n\nI'll search for information about NVIDIA datacenter GPU VRAM/memory capacities for these models.\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"NVIDIA Data Center GPU Specs: A Complete Comparison Guide | IntuitionLabs\",\"url\":\"https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/nvidia-data-center-gpu-specs\"},{\"title\":\"NVIDIA Data Center GPUs Explained: From A100 to B200 and Beyond\",\"url\":\"https://www.bentoml.com/blog/nvidia-data-center-gpus-explained-a100-h200-b200-and-beyond\"},{\"title\":\"GPU VRAM vs Memory Bandwidth for AI & LLMs | Ocolo Blog\",\"url\":\"https://blog.ocolo.io/gpu-vram-vs-memory-bandwidth-ai-llm/\"},{\"title\":\"Nvidia H100 GPU: Specs, VRAM, Price, and AI Performance\",\"url\":\"https://www.runpod.io/articles/guides/nvidia-h100\"},{\"title\":\"Hopper (microarchitecture) - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopper_(microarchitecture)\"},{\"title\":\"Why does an NVIDIA H100 80GB card offer 85.52 GB? – Jonathon Belotti [thundergolfer]\",\"url\":\"https://thundergolfer.com/blog/nvidia-gpu-memory-capacity\"},{\"title\":\"Nvidia B200 GPU: Specs, VRAM, Price, and AI Performance\",\"url\":\"https://www.runpod.io/articles/guides/nvidia-b200\"},{\"title\":\"NVIDIA H200 Vs H100 Vs A100 Vs L40S Vs L4 GPUs Compared\",\"url\":\"https://acecloud.ai/blog/nvidia-h200-vs-h100-vs-a100-vs-l40s-vs-l4/\"},{\"title\":\"Best NVIDIA GPUs for LLMs in 2026: Ranked by Use Case | Spheron Blog\",\"url\":\"https://www.spheron.network/blog/best-nvidia-gpus-for-llms/\"},{\"title\":\"Nvidia H200 GPU: Specs, VRAM, Price, and AI Performance\",\"url\":\"https://www.runpod.io/articles/guides/nvidia-h200-gpu\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of NVIDIA datacenter GPU VRAM/memory capacities based on the search results:\n\n## NVIDIA Datacenter GPU Memory Capacities\n\n### Hopper Architecture\n- **H100**: The Nvidia H100 has 80 GB of HBM3 memory (SXM variant) with approximately 3.35 TB/s of memory bandwidth. The PCIe variant also offers 80 GB but uses HBM2e memory with ~2 TB/s bandwidth. Notably, both variants are available in an 80 GB configuration; there is no 40 GB H100.\n\n- **H200**: The Nvidia H200 has 141 GB of HBM3e memory with approximately 4.8 TB/s of memory bandwidth. The memory upgrade comes from six stacks of 24 GB HBM3e (vs. five stacks of 16 GB HBM3 on the H100), delivering the capacity and bandwidth increases.\n\n### Ampere Architecture\n- **A100**: Available in two configurations — A100: up to 80 GB (also available in 40 GB variant). Memory bandwidth: A100 80GB: ~2 TB/s. The A100 also notably does not support FP8.\n\n### Blackwell Architecture\n- **B200**: Reported capacities vary slightly by source. Runpod lists it as 180 GB of HBM3e memory with approximately 8 TB/s of memory bandwidth. This is the highest VRAM capacity available on any single GPU and more than double the H100's 80 GB. Other sources cite a 192 GB figure — Spheron notes its 192 GB of HBM3e at 8 TB/s bandwidth means it can serve Llama 3.1 70B at FP16 on a single GPU with room to spare for large KV caches.\n\n- **B300**: A newer Blackwell Ultra variant — The B300's 288 GB fits 70B models in FP16 with over 100 GB to spare for KV cache and batch processing.\n\n### Ada Lovelace Architecture\n- **L40S**: Its 48 GB GDDR6 memory is often sufficient and delivers solid performance in modern production pipelines. Note that the L40/L40S Ada GPUs do not support MIG (they are pure graphics accelerators).\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| GPU | Architecture | VRAM | Memory Type | Bandwidth |\n|-----|-------------|------|-------------|-----------|\n| A100 | Ampere | 40 GB / 80 GB | HBM2e | ~2 TB/s |\n| V100 | Volta | 16/32 GB* | HBM2 | ~0.9 TB/s* |\n| L40S | Ada Lovelace | 48 GB | GDDR6 | ~0.9 TB/s |\n| H100 | Hopper | 80 GB | HBM3/HBM2e | 3.35 TB/s (SXM) |\n| H200 | Hopper | 141 GB | HBM3e | 4.8 TB/s |\n| B200 | Blackwell | 180–192 GB | HBM3e | 8 TB/s |\n| B300 | Blackwell Ultra | 288 GB | HBM3e | — |\n\n*Note: The search results did not contain specific details for the **V100** and **A10** GPUs you mentioned. Based on general knowledge, the V100 comes in 16 GB or 32 GB HBM2 configurations, and the A10 has 24 GB GDDR6. \n\n### Additional Context\nOn multi-GPU systems, memory is effectively pooled: the use of stacked DRAM (HBM2, HBM2e, HBM3e) on NVLink-connected boards effectively merges all GPU memory into one system. For example, an 8-GPU SXM node has 8×40 GB = 320 GB unified memory for an A100 system, or 8×80 GB=640 GB on H100.\n\nIt's also worth noting the distinction between marketing capacity and actual reported memory — NVIDIA GPUs substantially overprovision the gigabytes on their newer generation GPUs. The H200 product claims 141 GB but delivers almost 7% more memory.\n\nWould you like me to search for the specific V100 and A10 memory specifications to complete the picture?\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
